      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Gardner B. Weeks (d. 1886) was an American businessman.  He was intensely active in 
		agricultural matters in Central New York, including serving as Secretary of the American 
		Dairymen's Association.  He was involved in mining and smelting businesses and was apparently 
		the owner of a Syracuse, New York company that manufactured hay forks, railway conveyors and 
		other items.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Gardner B. Weeks Scrapbook</emph> consists of a large scrapbook 
			containing prospectuses, circulars, trade catalogs, broadsides, samples of printed ephemera, 
			and news clippings.  There are also foreign queries, testimonials, and two letters from W.E. 
			Dodge and Russell Sturgis.  Interspersed are personal items such as concert programs, a 
			Central City bank note, letters and drawings from family and friends, and more.</p>
			
			<p>Companies with which Weeks was involved, and which are represented in the scrapbook, 
			include the Pendery Mining Co. of Syracuse and Little Falls, the Syracuse &amp; Dumont 
			Consolidated Mining Company, Fisher &amp; Millis Hills Mining &amp; Smelting Co. (with mine 
			in North Carolina), Grappling Hay Forks and Railway Conveyors, and Weeks, Thompson &amp; Co. 
			Road Carts.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
